Our Objectives

Our project aims to bridge the gap between bioinformatics and practical agricultural applications through innovative synthetic biology approaches.

  • Create comprehensive genetic resources for agricultural improvement
  • Develop user-friendly tools for microbial genome analysis
  • Implement precision delivery systems for targeted biological interventions
  • Standardize modular cloning approaches for synthetic biology
INNOVATION IN SYNTHETIC BIOLOGY

Bridging computational and experimental approaches

Dataset Details

  • 5 Litchi Varieties

    糯米糍 (Nuomici), 桂味 (Guiwei), 怀枝 (Huaizhi), 金钟 (Jinzong), 河砂 (Hesha)

  • 7-Day Monitoring

    Daily measurements throughout the spoilage process

  • Dual Imaging

    RGB and infrared images for each sample

  • Biochemical Data

    pH levels and sugar content measurements

  • Open Access

    Available for research and commercial use under CC-BY license

Bio Knowledge Integration

Our system integrates comprehensive biological knowledge graphs that connect gene functions, metabolic pathways, and protein interactions. This allows the generative model to make biologically informed predictions based on established scientific literature and databases.

iGEM Database Integration

Seamless connection with the iGEM Parts Registry providing access to over 20,000 standardized biological parts. The generative model can leverage these pre-validated components to design more reliable genetic constructs with higher success rates.

Advanced Gene Analysis

Incorporates multi-omics data analysis pipelines that process gene expression, epigenetic modifications, and regulatory elements. The generative model uses this information to optimize gene sequence design for specific host organisms and environmental conditions.

Protein Structure Prediction

Integrates state-of-the-art protein folding prediction algorithms to model the 3D structure of designed proteins. This allows the generative model to optimize protein sequences for desired structural properties and functional interactions before experimental validation.

Population Material Production

Bridges computational design with experimental implementation by generating optimized protocols for scaled production of biological materials. The system considers yield optimization, scalability, and cost factors to translate designs into practical production processes.

Interactive Simulation Platform

U

I need a strong promoter.

Could you please specify your requirements? What is your engineered strain? Do you need any regulatory factors?

U

I need a constitutive promoter that works in E. coli.

I've found a common promoter for you in E. coli: J23119. It's derived from the T4 promoter and is widely used in synthetic biology. You can access its sequence via its part number.

U

Next, please design a validation plan for it.

Certainly. To validate this promoter, we need to assemble the other parts of an operon and find a suitable vector.

The operon also requires a ribosome binding site (RBS), a reporter gene, and a terminator. I have found a common RBS: BBa_K3763000, a repo
